Traveling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early tolay swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm. % Beyond the fact that an aban doned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick. on the Baltimore pike, there Is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken u pr delst , 411nd ~~l~tke. t -270==e rI~ The "Ington PolIed' Depart. ment, upon being notified et the raid. threw a cordon about'the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough prep aration. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveil lance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big au tomobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scat tered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpow ered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: Wil. liam Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the raigers left, more than two hours later. FVom fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approxhnately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolied from the building and leaded en the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4: o'clock to omaplete the loading of the carm van. Then the motorcycle outposts re ported the roads clear. The watch men were admonished against any attempt to escape and the caravan made off. Telephone Lines Cut. Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines 'had been cut and was forced 'to walk, a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff Jamee C. Jones was notified and telephoned the police at all nearby points to watch dvery road away from Frederick. Jn spite of the network, the ban dits managed to slip through, and no clue no to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jef ferson. it is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the samte men who rob~bed the distillery of 2W0 cases of whiskey Setember 9 la*. Much of the aeer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by boot leggers at a high prie. Posed ao Dry Agent. It is thought the truck train may have broken a pr delst , and ~~l~tke. t -270==e I The "Ington PolIce Department upon being notified at the raid. threw a cordon about the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the ranges left more than two hours later. From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolled from the building and leaded on the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4: o'clock to complete the loading of the caravan Then the motorcycle outposts reported the roads clear. The watch men were admonished against any attempt to escape and the caravan made off. Telephone Lines Cut. Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines had been cut and was forced to walk, a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff James C. Jones was notified and telephoned the police at all nearby points to watch dvery road away from Frederick In spite of the network, the bandits managed to slip through, and no clue no to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jefferson. it is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the same men who robbed the distillery of 200 cases of whiskey December 9 la*. Much of the deer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by bootleggers at a high price Posed as Dry Agent. The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who represented himself as an internal revenue agent from Washington appeared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way- in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death If they made any outcry or attempt to escape and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. Handkerchief were stuffed into their mouths and they were bound With the guards tied and aged, the bandits worked quickly. Tey appeared to have on plate knowledge of the location of the liquor, and lost no time opening the building. The trucks and touring cars

RAIDERS IN FREDERICK LAND HAUL OF $84,000 Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey Is Loaded Into Autos. Travelling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early today swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm. % Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken a pr delst, and ~~l~tke. t -270==e I The "Ington PolIce Department upon being notified at the raid. threw a cordon about the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the ranges left more than two hours later. From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolled from the building and leaded on the trucks and touring cars. A second, unidentified man was found in a truck and hauled away by two men who were on the other side of the building, who are reported to have kept an eye on the four other caravans. On the next morning, after an escort of forty miles of searchlight, they arrived at the Distillery in a van, which the four watchmen were riding in. On the next morning they saw that the distillery was still occupied and that there was a large crowd of men waiting for them. At this early hour, they were taken off by their motorbikes and taken to a storage area to be examined for evidence. Their bodies were subsequently disposed of by a warden and buried. After this day, and in the course of an inspection of the distillery, it is believed that the two watchmen were brought back to their places of rest and that the bodies recovered were indeed of the aged whiskey which they took, although this was not conclusive. The whiskey recovered was apparently more or less similar to those found in the old Whiskey Town of Chicago, but it was not until 1780. The discovery of the whiskey that day at a place unknown to the robbers did not result in their being murdered. The following day, the distillery was located by the following route, by way of the county, and in that place an independent, but respectable man, the Earl of Richmond, had set off to the Old Horpey Distillery in order to learn what to do in the matter. He had, at his request, received from the proprietors and operators of the Distillery Company (a company called 'C.R.P.' by his own nickname) of the distillery some whiskey which had been made on an island in North Africa. The proprietors, after their meeting with the estate agent of the distillery, and his wife, informed the owner that he would find it for him, and that it was as he had promised to use it, and that this was his plan for using it. He was then sent back to the distillery with his wife to see how they had obtained this whiskey and to inquire as to the proprietor's interest. A certain young man of the same name appeared in front of the proprietor and said that he had sent for this whiskey to him to obtain his business. His name was John B. Hampton. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveil lance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big au tomobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scat tered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpow ered the three watchmen-John R. Travelling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early today swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm. % Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken a pr delst , and ~~l~tke. t -270==e I The "Ington PolIce Department upon being notified at the raid. threw a cordon about the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the ranges left more than two hours later. From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolled from the building and leaded on the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4: o'clock to complete the loading of the caravan Then the motorcycle outposts reported the roads clear. The watch men were admonished against any attempt to escape and the caravan made off. Telephone Lines Cut. Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines had been cut and was forced to walk, a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff James C. Jones was notified and telephoned the police at all nearby points to watch dvery road away from Frederick In spite of the network, the bandits managed to slip through, and no clue no to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jefferson. it is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the same men who robbed the distillery of 200 cases of whiskey December 9 la*. Much of the deer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by bootleggers at a high price Posed as Dry Agent. The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who represented himself as an internal revenue agent from Washington appeared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way- in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death If they made any outcry or attempt to escape and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. Handkerchief were stuffed into their mouths and they were bound With the guards tied and aged, the bandits worked quickly. Tey appeared to have on plate knowledge of the location of the liquor, and lost no time opening the building. The trucks and touring cars

prediction.region:
RAIDERS IN FREDERICK LAND HAUL OF $84,000 

Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey Is Loaded Into Autos. 

Travelling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early today swooped down on the Old Harper Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm.

Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken apart and leaked.

The Washington Police Department upon being notified of the raid, threw a cordon about the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen.

Seven Autos In Raid.

With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen- John R. Hemp, of Burkittsville, Md.; William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the raiders left more than two hours later.

From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons in all, were rolled from the building and loaded on the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4 o'clock to complete the loading of the caravan. Then the motorcycle outposts reported the roads clear. The watchmen were admonished against any attempt to escape and the caravan made off.

Telephone Lines Cut.

Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines had been cut and was forced to walk a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff James C. Jones was notified and telephoned the police in all nearby points to watch every road away from Frederick. In spite of the network, the bandits managed to slip through, and no clue as to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jefferson. It is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the same men who robbed the distillery of 200 cases of whiskey December 9 last. Much of the deer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by bootleggers at a high price.

Posed as Dry Agent.

The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who represented himself as an internal revenue agent from Washington appeared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death if they made any outcry or attempt to escape, and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. Handkerchiefs were stuffed into their mouths and they were bound. With the guards tied and aged, the bandits worked quickly. They appeared to have expert knowledge of the location of the liquor, and lost no time opening the building. The trucks and touring cars were then loaded with the stolen liquor.

AN ACT REGARDING THE IMPORTANCE OF SUCH A DEAL. This act is hereby enacted to amend the act (or any other legislation) of April 19, 1906, as written, and is hereby further amended and further expanded in such a way as to make it as follows:1. To authorize the state to, within one year after April 19, 1906, issue bonds to purchase land for the public good, such bonds to be issued, with interest from ten per cent to fifty per cent, of the original price, and may be renewed in the same manner, or in the manner in which they were issued. The bonds may also be issued in the same manner as bonds issued by other departments. Any person, by written consent, may place bonds, and other goods of the same type, in which case the bondholders are required to make their representations and pay any other penalty which the court may deem reasonable in this case.

prediction.region: were locked and the old whiskey rolled into the rear of each. Tey then went to the rear of the building, unloaded their truck load, and took their turn unloading the cars. The entire caravan was then driven to the front of the distillery, and after a brief halt, the twenty-one bandits disappeared. Sheriff Jones was told that the entire caravan and its contents were searched and the contents were found to contain a large quantity of whisky. Some of the whiskey was seized, and a case of it was taken from the caravan and placed on the table of the sheriff. The watchmen were finally released at 3.30. The robbery has been made public by the Government in an official statement, announcing that an investigation was being held for the recovery of the stolen liquor.</s>

prediction.region: were brought up to the distillery. The watchmen were carried from the building, one at a time, and tied to trees near by, to prevent their escape. They said they were not beaten, and that nothing was taken from them. When the whiskey was loaded on the trucks and autos, the bandits made their way out of the building, which was locked and guarded by their guards, and the caravan started, to the north. Hemp's Story Told to Police. Hemp, in telling his story to the police, said the "agent" made a thorough search of the building and finally told the watchmen he had found all the whiskey. He said the man then walked across the floor of the room and was joined by another bandit. who brought out a long-handled screw driver and turned the cap off one of the barrels. He said the bandits began transferring the liquor to the trucks. They said they were acting under instructions from Washington. Hemp said he knew there was none of the distillery's whiskey in the building, and told the men to turn the cap off a barrel of whiskey which had been placed in the office for their use. The bandits did so, and then Hemp pretended to be frightened and pleaded for his life. "When I pretended to be frightened, they said we were to walk away from the office, and that we would not be harmed," Hemp said. "We walked down the road for some distance, and then we decided to escape. They made us walk so far that we were afraid we might lose the trucks. "I ran back through the field. When I looked back I saw one of the trucks turn from the highway into the fields, and the others followed. I could see the cars for a long time and finally gave it up, as I knew that the pursuit would be useless. I finally got back to the distillery and notified the sheriff. When I broke loose, I had to walk a long distance before I found any place to telephone for assistance. "When we got there, it was almost two o'clock. I knew the bandits were so far ahead that they could not be overtaken." Sheriff Jones' Men Busy. The sheriff's men were busy all day yesterday following up the report, but no clews were obtained until after midnight, when a patrolman learned that a truck load of stolen whiskey had been found near Jefferson, three miles from Frederick. The truck had been abandoned, and was found by Mr. and Mrs. John M. Carroll, who lives on the road near Jefferson. "I found the liquor there at three o'clock this morning. I went down and found a note in the cab, and at once telephoned the police and the sheriff." The note, addressed to Hemp and Hart, stated: "The truck you left has been overtaken by the authorities. Good luck to you." The truck had been abandoned with the door open, and a heavy rock had been placed on the brake. The police are trying to trace the origin of the note, and believe that it is the work of the same man who broke into the office at the distillery. The Sheriff has been busy rounding up his men and establishing a watch about the entire State. He has assigned one deputy to watch the road from Frederick to Washington, and a special squad has been organized. The whiskey which was taken from the distillery was "barrel proof," a grade which is sold at $10 per gallon, and which is kept in barrels for many years before it is sold. The whiskey stolen was estimated to be worth from $75 to $84,000, but as it is barrel proof, it would be worth much more when sold in bottles. "The whiskey was old and had not been distilled for ten years. It was the best whiskey which had been made there. The bandits must have known that." -The New York Tribune. H. 8. TANK HAS TWO KNIGHT

prediction.region:
Raiders in Frederick Land Haul of $84,000: Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey is Loaded into Autos

Traveling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early today swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery, near Frederick, MD, and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm.

Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken a part, and the police are investigating.

The Washington Police Department, upon being notified of the raid, threw a cordon about the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies who learned every movement of the watchmen.

Seven Autos in Raid

With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen - John R. Hemp of Burkettaville, MD; William Hart of Baltimore; and John Moredock of Baltimore.

The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged, and an armed man stood over them until the raiders left more than two hours later. From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons in all, were rolled from the building and loaded onto the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4 o'clock to complete the loading of the caravan. Then, the motorcycle outposts reported the roads clear. The watchmen were admonished against any attempt to escape, and the caravan made off.

Telephone Lines Cut

Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines had been cut and was forced to walk a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff James C. Jones was notified and began the search for the bandits.

While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the ranges left more than two hours later. From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolled from the building and leaded on the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4: o'clock to complete the loading of the caravan Then the motorcycle outposts reported the roads clear. The watch men were admonished against any attempt to escape and the caravan made off. Telephone Lines Cut. Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines had been cut and was forced to walk, a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff James C. Jones was notified and telephoned the police at all nearby points to watch dvery road away from Frederick In spite of the network, the bandits managed to slip through, and no clue no to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jefferson. it is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the same men who robbed the distillery of 200 cases of whiskey December 9 la*. Much of the deer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by bootleggers at a high price Posed as Dry Agent. The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who represented himself as an internal revenue agent from Washington appeared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way- in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death If they made any outcry or attempt to escape and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. Handkerchief were stuffed into their mouths and they were bound With the guards tied and aged, the bandits worked quickly. prediction.region: were all parked in the front yard, near the distillery, where the motorcycle men could guard them. The bandits worked in absolute silence, and not a single shot was fired throughout the raid. The Old Horpey distillery is in a secluded place in a valley surrounded by hills, and it would seem that the bandits had to move a long distance, on good roads, to reach the Baltimore pike. A large number of bottles of "Burgundy" whiskey were discovered by the police. No clue has yet been found as to the whereabouts of the whiskey stolen. It is the belief of Sheriff Jones that it has been brought to Washington, as the motor cars used in the raid are too slow to make the journey to Baltimore and points beyond the city without being delayed at some way station. The police of Washington have been instructed to be on the lookout for the stolen liquor, and to apprehend the bandits if they show up. They are believed to be armed men. A BIG WHISKEY RAID The police department here has been busy all morning rounding up a gang of bootleggers. It is a big raid and a big haul was made by the police. The bootleggers have been very active in recent months, but their activity has been on the increase since the 13th amendment came into force. They are taking a chance by selling to the public in Washington at $5.00 and $6.00 a gallon, when they know it costs them only 65 cents. The police are after them and have been making some big hauls. The liquor is being brought in by the wagon load and the gangs that are bringing it in are very daring. They drive the wagons into the parks and other secluded places, where they can unload. Then they conceal the liquor where they hope to get it later. A lot of the gangs are operating in the parks and a number of officers are out after them. It is a hard job to locate them and bring them to justice. Many of them are armed and they make a fierce resistance when they are arrested. The police have discovered that one gang that has been working the parks is located somewhere in Southern Maryland. They have got the police on their track and soon they will be in the lockup. It is believed they are the gang that raided the old Horpey Distillery and took $84,000 worth of whiskey. It Is thought they are going to unload the whiskey on the streets and sell it to the public. They are also taking a chance that they may be caught and then it will be very bad for them. The police have the gangs on the run, and in a few days they will be out of business.

were packed and loaded. The watchmen, who had not been seen at the distillery for a few hours, came in and reported to the officer the contents of the caravan at 1 o'clock at night. The officer was immediately informed of the loss of life. The caravan was taken back to Maryland where the two watchmen were arrested and charged with treason. They were also charged with robbery and battery. The watchmen were found safe but the men who were captured were not convicted. The other bandits were sentenced to death. They were convicted in November of the year in which the accident occurred, but in November, 1916, were not released. Hemp had been sentenced to death in February of 1917, and Moredock and Hart, who were both present in the place of the accident, were sentenced in May of 1917. A telegram from Washington informed the Government that the bandits had been released, and the caravan was loaded back to Baltimore in July of 1916, but there was no trace of the watchmen until October of that year, when a notice was sent to the citizens informing them that all had been freed. The government was informed that the men who had been freed were in possession of large quantities of Old Horpey whiskey and that they had to be released. The men who were taken prisoners were freed in July of 1917. They had been freed because the authorities had decided that they would not be subject to further interrogation.
Hemp, in his account of the accident in Maryland, said of the men who were taken prisoner that they had been freed because the authorities had decided to continue on interrogating them in the same way in which they were freed. He then said that the men who were released by that decision had been locked up at Jefferson, MD. for an extended period of time. They had been locked up for several years and had been sent to Frederick, Md., to be interrogated on charges related to their crime. He added that his wife had taken him back to Baltimore to be interrogated because he had not returned to Maryland in his own person, but that the men who had been released by that decision had been locked up at Jefferson for an extended period of time. He had only been able to obtain a confession from a prisoner who had been detained at Jefferson for several days. The authorities in Maryland, after many days of deliberation and trial and many investigations, had concluded that the men who had been released had been released because the authorities had decided to continue on interrogating them in the same way in which they were freed. These men were sent to Maryland, and were found in Maryland in December of 1916. The men who were liberated were released because the authorities were convinced that they had been subject to further interrogation in the same way in which they were freed. When a man is released he will be informed as to all the charges against him. The men who were released were taken back to Maryland in November of 1918, and were in Maryland in December of the same year. They were held there for one month and taken back to Frederick, Md. and to Baltimore, then to Jefferson, MD., where they were released in March of 1919. During this time Hemp and his colleagues were held in Jefferson until June, 1920, when they were released on the assumption that they had committed the crime of treason. Their release from Jefferson, Maryland, was because the authorities had determined that they had not committed any crime in this district. They were transferred to Frederick, Maryland, and then to Baltimore, then to Jefferson, Maryland, where they were released in July of 1919.
Hemp was in Maryland for many months before he left the District, and his account shows that the government had a good deal of trouble in the vicinity of Jefferson, since there were rumors of robberies there and many of the watchmen had no idea of the location of the whiskey. groundtruth.region: RAIDERS IN FREDER IC K LAND HAUL OF $84,000 Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey Is Load eld Into Autos. Traveling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early tolay swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm. % Beyond the fact that an aban doned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick. on the Baltimore pike, there Is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken u pr delst , 411nd ~~l~tke. t -270==e rI~ The "Ington PolIed' Depart. ment, upon being notified et the raid. threw a cordon about'the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough prep aration. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveil lance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big au tomobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scat tered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpow ered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: Wil. liam Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the raigers left, more than two hours later. FVom fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approxhnately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolied from the building and leaded en the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4: o'clock to omaplete the loading of the carm van. Then the motorcycle outposts re ported the roads clear. The watch men were admonished against any attempt to escape and the caravan made off. Telephone Lines Cut. Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines 'had been cut and was forced 'to walk, a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff Jamee C. Jones was notified and telephoned the police at all nearby points to watch dvery road away from Frederick. Jn spite of the network, the ban dits managed to slip through, and no clue no to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jef ferson. it is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the samte men who rob~bed the distillery of 2W0 cases of whiskey Setember 9 la*. Much of the aeer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by boot leggers at a high prie. Posed ao Dry Agent. The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who repre sented himself as an Internal reve nue agent from Washington ap peared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way- in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death If they made any outcry or attempt to escape and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. Handkerchief. were stuffed into their mouths and they were bound With the guards tied and gged, the bandits worked quickly. Tey appeared to have om plate knowi edge of the location of the liquor, and loSt no time opening the build ing. The trucks and touring cars

prediction.region: RAIDERS STEAL $84,000 WORTH OF WHISKEY FROM HORPEY DISTILLERY IN FREDERICK Watchmen Bound and Gagged During the Robbery. Three Government watchmen were tied up and threatened with death during a robbery of the Old Horpey Distillery in Frederick, MD. Early this morning, twenty armed bandits, traveling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, stole $84,000 worth of whiskey. Although an abandoned truck with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there are no leads on the whereabouts of the bandits. After preparation spanning several days, the bandits arrived at the distillery with fifteen breaking into the office to subdue the three watchmen. The aged whiskey, around 2,106 gallons, was loaded onto trucks and touring cars, taking the robbers until nearly 4 a.m. to complete the loading. The roads were reported clear by the motorcycle outposts, and the caravan left under the watchful eye of an armed man, threatening the watchmen if they tried to escape. Sheriff James C. Jones was notified, and the Washington Police Department placed a cordon around the city, watching every road that the bandits might use to transport the stolen whiskey into the District. Hemp, a watchman, managed to free himself and informed the authorities after walking a long distance since the telephone lines had been cut.

Much of the deer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by bootleggers at a high price Posed as Dry Agent. The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who represented himself as an internal revenue agent from Washington appeared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way- in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death If they made any outcry or attempt to escape and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. Handkerchief were stuffed into their mouths and they were bound With the guards tied and aged, the bandits worked quickly. Tey appeared to have on plate knowledge of the location of the liquor, and lost no time opening the building. The trucks and touring cars were left on the streets as a back guard, and a guard was employed to protect them. About four-thirty in the afternoon, a car carrying the confiscated liquor was found at a business office in the city. The guards and the car driver were released and left for Washington. There was a call to the police for a search of the premises, and on finding the stolen liquor, a man in the car, whose name was not given, confessed that he was a local liquor agent. He said that when he arrived in Washington, a fellow agent, who had just arrived from Maryland, had asked him for the liquor. In a state of disbelief the agent said he had seen the man in his apartment, but that the man's friend had been drinking at a bar on the way. A man from the nearby town of Burmester was charged with assisting the robbery, and was arrested. He was convicted of assisting the robbery and was sentenced to six years in prison. The robbery was made by the man who was driving the car and the other man whose name was not given. The man who drove the car is also suspected of helping the robbers. There are no clues to the direction taken by the caravan or the location of the trailer. The bandits were described as being black, between the ages of twenty-three and thirty, standing about five feet four inches tall. Their attire was described as being black and wearing a yellow cowboy hat with a red, green, and blue striped raiment. Their appearance and surroundings were unknown. The thieves carried a number of handguns and pistols and a large load of ammo was found in the front seat of the car. The thieves are described as wearing black trousers and long coats, with black boots. They were driven by a man who had been with the car, while another man carried the weapon from the rear seat. A second car with three other men was also seen by the bandits in a nearby state of confusion. Two of the men were seen at the same time carrying the rifle and ammunition, while the third man carried a revolver. The stolen liquor was carried from a car driven by one of the thieves to Washington by another man, with the gun on his person. The two men were charged with aiding and abetting the robbery and were convicted of robbery. The burglary took place in the early morning hours. It is believed that the robbers entered the distillery and took the whiskey while the watchmen were asleep. The thieves were captured shortly before midnight on the Baltimore-Washington National Highway near Washington, Md. The liquor was purchased from the distillery, the money was collected, and the liquor was sent to Washington to be sold in the United States. The road from Maryland was closed for several hours, and on getting to Washington police sent two of the bandits over the pike to an isolated area where they were arrested. Two of the guards were shot and killed, and the fourth was wounded in the chest. They are expected to be prosecuted as a gang. A sheriff's deputy was injured in the shooting. In Washington, Maryland, Sheriff Jones gave orders for a search of all areas of the city, including every public road, public water system, sewer, road, and all other public and private roads into the District. His order states, "The public shall not be allowed to approach this property until this office has been properly informed." His order also says, "If the people or any agents thereof should attempt to enter thedistillery and steal liquor and cash, there shall be the immediate arrest and prosecution of the offenders." Police are in a panic and a sheriff's deputy was seriously injured in the shootout with the thieves. In the afternoon sheriff Jones was received at Baltimore by Chief Judge James H. White of the District Court of Appeals. Judge White was in attendance, and was informed that the sheriff was being relieved

Jones was notified and telephoned the police at all nearby points to watch dvery road away from Frederick In spite of the network, the bandits managed to slip through, and no clue no to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jefferson. it is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the same men who robbed the distillery of 200 cases of whiskey December 9 la*. Much of the deer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by bootleggers at a high price Posed as Dry Agent. The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who represented himself as an internal revenue agent from Washington appeared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way- in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death If they made any outcry or attempt to escape and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. The other body was that of John Hemp, who, it is believed, fell from the roof of the building. The watchmen described the bandit as about 5 feet 3 inches tall, of medium build and of a light complexion. He was about 35 years of age and was about to be married. His hair was thinning and he wore a full beard. The men did not speak English. The bandits had no firearms and carried no revolvers. All the time they were here, their movements were watched and the sheriff was told every detail. He and other officers of the law were stationed at all approaches to the city and a special police detail was engaged in securing evidence. The raiders were dressed in black and wore black masks over their faces. It is believed that they were well known to the local bootleggers. An Important Raid. The raid was an important one, as it marked the first time ever that an internal revenue agent had been taken for a bootlegger. The raiders were well prepared for the raid. A number of them had been here before and knew every nook and corner. The whiskey raid was the first successful raid ever made by the bootleggers in Frederick. They will probably raid again. The hand trucks were then taken to the railroad station where the liquor was transferred into a train. The caravan broke away from the train and then returned to Frederick, where the bandits proceeded to open the building, remove the barrels and load the whiskey into the trucks. They were in charge of the caravan for some distance and the caravan was then forced on by the authorities, until it was beyond reach. The police have made several arrests in connection with the affair. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the ranges left more than two hours later. From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolled from the building and leaded on the trucks and touring cars. RAIDERS IN FREDERICK LAND HAUL OF $84,000
The watchmen soon realized that the man was a desperate man who wanted a last resort before he was killed. A few minutes later he came back carrying a box of gunpowder and told the watchmen that he wanted to burn the house. They resisted him vigorously, but were beaten to submission. When they finally surrendered to the authorities, the man threw the gunpowder into the kitchen and took possession of the safe and the key. Sheriff Jones was then told that it would be impossible to open the safe without the key. As the guards were brought out of the office, they were bound with heavy cords. One guard, a negro, who had worked in the office was released, and left in the hands of the watchmen, who told him to watch the door to keep out the bandits. Sheriff Jones was notified that the bandits had a machine gun, and were expected to be there a few minutes later. They were, however, never seen again. The watchmen were placed in an alley and then sent to the hospital. The hospital at which they were taken was a few miles away. They were taken out of the alley at once, and given a cold drink of water, to which they gave much attention. Later they were taken to the State jail, where they were allowed to sleep until it was judged necessary to place them in custody of the Washington authorities. In the meantime the district attorney at Washington was notified of the raid and was advised by the Federal marshal to send a police patrol on horseback to look for the caravan. The sheriff informed the Washington authorities that he was unable to reach the area until after the police patrol had returned to the city, so the district attorney at Washington called for the help of a cavalry detachment. The detachment was sent to the hospital where they stayed for several days to care for the injured, and then was sent back to Washington with the sheriff. The district attorney at Washington told Sheriff Jones that he had ordered a patrol of cavalry to proceed along the Baltimore and Washington Railroad, to look for the caravan. He advised him to wait until the patrol had returned. Sheriff Jones was then notified that the bandits were on horseback, and he was advised to make good his preparations to repel the raiders, and to get his cavalry to prepare to ride with the patrol. He was instructed to prepare for all eventualities, and to get his men to wear light steel shoes, heavy leather boots, and light saddle armor.
In the meantime the Federal marshal telephoned the Washington authorities to advise that the Federal troops were awaiting the arrival of the cavalry detachment. The cavalry was sent back to Washington at once. Sheriff Jones was then informed that the cavalry were awaiting orders to proceed against the bandits. It was a difficult case, since there was no definite information to guide the patrol. There was not a single witness. In addition, the cavalry had only one field hospital to deal with the casualties, and the Federal marshal advised Sheriff Jones that the men were all severely wounded. The cavalry remained at the hospital until the Federal marshal returned, and then started on the patrol, the detachment proceeding along the Baltimore and Washington Railroad. As they neared the town of Wilkesbarre, the cavalry was met by the bandits, who fled to a point where they could easily see the cavalry coming. Sheriff Jones was informed that the cavalry were well-armed and he was advised that the patrol was outnumbered by the bandits. The cavalry were then told to wait, and the bandits were seen to move on again. They continued on until the cavalry stopped the men and demanded their passports. The cavalry told them that they were on a search and that they were free to leave, but were advised to go to the nearest hotel and report there. After this warning, the cavalry retreated to their hotel in the city. The patrol went up to the hotel where they saw three men who told them that they were on a search for the bandits, and were in possession of an important piece of information about their movements. RAIDERS IN FREDERICK LAND HAUL OF $84,000 Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey Is Loaded Into Autos. Travelling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early today swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm. % Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken a pr delst, and ~~l~tke. t -270==e I The "Ington PolIce Department upon being notified at the raid. threw a cordon about the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the ranges left more than two hours later. From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolled from the building and leaded on the trucks and touring cars. A second, unidentified man was found in a truck and hauled away by two men who were on the other side of the building, who are reported to have kept an eye on the four other caravans. On the next morning, after an escort of forty miles of searchlight, they arrived at the Distillery in a van, which the four watchmen were riding in. On the next morning they saw that the distillery was still occupied and that there was a large crowd of men waiting for them. At this early hour, they were taken off by their motorbikes and taken to a storage area to be examined for evidence. Their bodies were subsequently disposed of by a warden and buried. After this day, and in the course of an inspection of the distillery, it is believed that the two watchmen were brought back to their places of rest and that the bodies recovered were indeed of the aged whiskey which they took, although this was not conclusive. The whiskey recovered was apparently more or less similar to those found in the old Whiskey Town of Chicago, but it was not until 1780. The discovery of the whiskey that day at a place unknown to the robbers did not result in their being murdered. The following day, the distillery was located by the following route, by way of the county, and in that place an independent, but respectable man, the Earl of Richmond, had set off to the Old Horpey Distillery in order to learn what to do in the matter. He had, at his request, received from the proprietors and operators of the Distillery Company (a company called 'C.R.P.' by his own nickname) of the distillery some whiskey which had been made on an island in North Africa. The proprietors, after their meeting with the estate agent of the distillery, and his wife, informed the owner that he would find it for him, and that it was as he had promised to use it, and that this was his plan for using it. He was then sent back to the distillery with his wife to see how they had obtained this whiskey and to inquire as to the proprietor's interest. A certain young man of the same name appeared in front of the proprietor and said that he had sent for this whiskey to him to obtain his business. His name was John B. Hampton. In a letter he had received from the owner of the Distillery, dated January 28, 1844, he asked for a "salt and pepper" of whiskey,

All but one of the guards had been killed during the previous attack. The men remained on the field in line and on the watch.

SOME WORKS:
The three watchmen, who had not been killed during the previous attack, were not all in the same group of guards. At this time the group of guards had been composed of one man and two men
groundtruth.region: RAIDERS IN FREDER IC K LAND HAUL OF $84,000 Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey Is Load eld Into Autos. Traveling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early tolay swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm. % Beyond the fact that an aban doned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick. on the Baltimore pike, there Is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken u pr delst , 411nd ~~l~tke. t -270==e rI~ The "Ington PolIed' Depart. ment, upon being notified et the raid. threw a cordon about'the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough prep aration. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveil lance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big au tomobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scat tered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpow ered the three watchmen-John R. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: Wil. liam Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the raigers left, more than two hours later. FVom fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approxhnately 2,106 gallons In all, was rolied from the building and leaded en the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4: o'clock to omaplete the loading of the carm van. Then the motorcycle outposts re ported the roads clear. The watch men were admonished against any attempt to escape and the caravan made off. Telephone Lines Cut. Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines 'had been cut and was forced 'to walk, a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff Jamee C. Jones was notified and telephoned the police at all nearby points to watch dvery road away from Frederick. Jn spite of the network, the ban dits managed to slip through, and no clue no to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jef ferson. it is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the samte men who rob~bed the distillery of 2W0 cases of whiskey Setember 9 la*. Much of the aeer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by boot leggers at a high prie. Posed ao Dry Agent. The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who repre sented himself as an Internal reve nue agent from Washington ap peared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way- in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death If they made any outcry or attempt to escape and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. Handkerchief. were stuffed into their mouths and they were bound With the guards tied and gged, the bandits worked quickly. Tey appeared to have om plate knowi edge of the location of the liquor, and loSt no time opening the build ing. The trucks and touring cars

prediction.region: A BRIDGE. The automobile, carrying the caravan's body and one of the watchmen, was stopped at a bridge, between Baltimore and Fredericksburg. The motorcycle driver had gone mad by the time it came under attack and was taken into custody. He had been a cop at the home, but was now a judge. The motorcade, with his wife, was now in possession of the two watchmen who had been shot and killed by the bandits. The motorcycle man, the watchman, and a woman were taken from under his belt, and tied with wire. One of the motorcycles was shot and killed.</s>

prediction.region:
RAIDERS IN FREDERICK LAND HAUL OF $84,000 

Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey Is Loaded Into Autos. 

Travelling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early today swooped down on the Old Harper Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm.

Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken apart and leaked.

The Washington Police Department upon being notified of the raid, threw a cordon about the city, and close watch was kept on every road which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen.

Seven Autos In Raid.

With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen- John R. Hemp, of Burkittsville, Md.; William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged and an armed man stood over them until the raiders left more than two hours later.

From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons in all, were rolled from the building and loaded on the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4 o'clock to complete the loading of the caravan. Then the motorcycle outposts reported the roads clear. The watchmen were admonished against any attempt to escape and the caravan made off.

Telephone Lines Cut.

Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines had been cut and was forced to walk a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff James C. Jones was notified and telephoned the police in all nearby points to watch every road away from Frederick. In spite of the network, the bandits managed to slip through, and no clue as to the direction they took has been discovered, except for the abandoned truck at Jefferson. It is the belief of Sheriff Jones that the bandits were the same men who robbed the distillery of 200 cases of whiskey December 9 last. Much of the deer liquor was brought to Washington on that occasion and was sold by bootleggers at a high price.

Posed as Dry Agent.

The watchmen told Sheriff Jones that at 2 o'clock a man who represented himself as an internal revenue agent from Washington appeared at the door of the office and demanded admittance. As the door was opened, his confederates pushed their way in with drawn revolvers. The watchmen were threatened with death if they made any outcry or attempt to escape, and one shot was fired by way of warning. Then the watchmen were backed against the wall, disarmed, and tied hand and foot with heavy cords. Handkerchiefs were stuffed into their mouths and they were bound. With the guards tied and aged, the bandits worked quickly. They appeared to have expert knowledge of the location of the liquor, and lost no time opening the building. The trucks and touring cars were then loaded with the stolen liquor.

The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies, who learned every movement of the watchmen. Seven Autos In Raid. Hemp, of Burkettaville, Md.: William Hart, of Baltimore, and John Moredock. of Baltimore. prediction.region:
were loaded with whiskey, and then the bandits began their ride, heading for Howard County, where the liquor was being sold in barrels. A few miles beyond Howard County the men stopped and, with the whiskey in hand, stole two wagons from a farm. They left the wagons empty and drove off. The following day the cars, carrying whiskey in barrels, left Washington and turned west on the Baltimore and Ohio road. They were driven into Howard County. The whiskey was left in barrels on the farms and was picked up by the bandits when they came to Howard County. The whiskey was sold at a high price on the black market and the proceeds were taken from the county and district treasury. The whiskey was sold by bootleggers at from $300 to $400 per gallon. The whiskey was stolen from the distillery at a cost of at least $84,000, and this crime is the second of a long line of burglaries of old distilleries. A number of cases of whiskey theft have occurred over the years In recent years. The Washington distillery was robbed of about 1,200 cases of whiskey and the Baltimore distillery. was robbed of about 600 cases of whiskey. The last crime, a burglary of the old distillery, was committed in December. The police of Howard County are confident in their investigation of the matter and will make a full report if requested.

Hemp said: "If you have a headache and you go into the store and get a bottle of water for me, I will go into the store and get the water for you. I have to tell you, that's all for the business. prediction.region: with the stolen liquor loaded, soon appeared and were followed by the motorcycles. The stolen liquor has been sold at $6,000 to $8,000 a cask. When a portion was sold here the price was $8,000. The stolen whiskey was estimated at 3,000 gallons. This leaves 200 cases which were sold elsewhere for about $4,000 a cask. The aged whiskey was stored in the underground cellars, and the bandits had no difficulty in locating it. The Old Horpey Distillery is considered one of the finest in Maryland and the bandits took only the aged whiskey. They destroyed the new liquor. The whiskey in the warehouse is not stored In kegs but in large tanks. The stolen liquor has been estimated at 30 years old. The 250 barrels which were taken in the December raid were said to be 30 years old and were sold for $8,000 a cask, It is thought the bandits will try to sell this latest theft of whiskey as a raid upon Government property. The distillery was sold by a foreclosure court in 1912 and the Government then placed watchmen there. The watchmen are paid at the rate of $2 a day. The Internal Revenue Department was notified of the raid. In addition to the loss of the whiskey and the money to be paid to the bandits, the Government will be called upon to pay to the watchmen for the loss of three days' pay. prediction.region:
Raiders in Frederick Land Haul of $84,000

Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey is Loaded into Autos.

Traveling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits early today swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery, near Frederick, Md., and made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three Government watchmen bound and gagged, under threat of instant death if they attempted to raise an alarm.

Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan. It is thought the truck train may have broken a part and left the scene.

The Washington Police Department, upon being notified of the raid, threw a cordon around the city, and a close watch was kept on every road by which the stolen liquor might be brought into the District. The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies who learned every movement of the watchmen.

Seven Autos in Raid

With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen - John R. Hemp of Burkittsville, Md.; William Hart of Baltimore, and John Moredock of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged, and an armed man stood over them until the raiders left more than two hours later.

From fifty to sixty barrels of the aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons in all, were rolled from the building and loaded onto the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4 o'clock to complete the loading of the caravan. Then the motorcycle outposts reported the roads clear. The watchmen were admonished against any attempt to escape, and the caravan made off.

Telephone Lines Cut

Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines had been cut and was forced to walk a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff James C. Jones

prediction.region: stood waiting In the cold outside. A lighted cigarette was placed In the watchmen's mouths as a threat. "If you make the least Outcry," the bandits warned them, "we will finish you and the caravan will be on its way before the police arrive. So help us God. We will do it!" The three men were helpless in their bonds. and could do nothing but hold their heads erect in shame. They were released only after the whiskey truck had passed the building. Bandits Masked. Sheriff Jones says there was no doubt the bandits were armed with automatic revolvers and machine guns. All were masked and wore long coats. They were all men who could ride. The stolen whiskey has been valued at $84,000. There is a reward of $10,000 offered by the distillery people for the capture of the bandits. The distillery Is a small one. operated by John J. Gorman. who owns a large plant at Hagerstown, Md. About 30 barrels of liquor a week are made there. The whiskey was in the process of maturing before bottling and was considered an aged brand. "We are sorry to lose any amount of liquor. but the loss will not materially affect the distillery people," said Mr. Gorman, today. "They are confident they can put a stop to the operations of the bandits, and, even if they cannot, the price paid by the whiskey peddlers for whiskey is too high to make the losses very serious. The distillery people will have more than they have had. There were about 100 barrels in the distillery, and that is a very small proportion of what was made." The police say they have no clue to the direction taken by the motor-caravan. "We can offer no hope whatever of capturing the bandits," said Sheriff Jones, "as there were about 30 of them. They took all possible care in making their getaway and they have plenty of time before any of them can be taken. As long as they keep off the roads they will escape, and they will be difficult to overtake. If they keep to the hills and mountain roads, they will be hard to find. There is a possibility that they may break into the District from the south, and they might even slip into Virginia from Maryland. There is no point to which they can be hurried that will result in their being captured. All efforts will be made to capture them, and when they are captured, every effort will be made to get them before a jury, but there is very little likelihood that they can be overtaken. They are well known in the District, and they are sure to be armed with automatics and machine guns. I am very certain that if they had to pass through the District, they would be as cautious as possible, and they would probably find means of entering some town of the North Carolina mountains. There is no possibility of a mistake that they would not have taken every precaution. They are well known in the District and in all the northern cities." Sheriff Jones, however, said he had no knowledge of a special watch being established at any of the mountain towns, as the only possibility would be in Virginia. "I have no knowledge of any watch established, but if they are going to Virginia, they are going to pass by Virginia and North Carolina towns, and if any of these towns have been put on their guard I have not heard of it. In Virginia, at least, it is difficult to believe that any special watch will have been established. Sheriff Jones said that there was no way of knowing the location of the distillery. and the police were now searching the hills about Middletown for any suspicious signs of an auto or truck. The raid was planned with care. The motorcycle scouts were sent out on the two roads nearest the distillery at 3 a. m. By that time, the caravan had been loaded and the trucks and touring cars started on their way to the District. The scouts reported that the highways were clear as far as they had gone.

were also removed from the distillery. A week later er and R. A. Ehrlich, of Baltimore. It was rumored that the bandits had taken out some of the liquor and had sold it for the bootlegger, but the real evidence is that they were still in possession of about 100 cases. The watchmen are quite skeptical that this was a fraud; they have known the bandits for many years. An Inquiry Into The Business of The Distillery, Baltimore. No evidence is to be had as to what the bandits intended to do with the rest of the whiskey, except that the man who was charged with the robbery of the distillery, an old acquaintance of the Bandits, was released.
The raid of the distillery at Jefferson, Md., had been followed by a much larger raid. The raid was held to take place during a winter vacation. The governor sent several deputies, some of whom were on the alert, and also an officer of the United States army. When the governor got on his radio, he said there was no evidence in the building of any weapons. The governor then asked the committee to look for clues, and the committee found that no evidence of any weapons was found. But the committee also noted that a shot of gunpowder had been thrown in the place, which was apparently a signal for an attack on the distillery. The committee found no evidence that anyone had intentionally shot or had fired shots at the distillery.
The governor then took possession of the distillery. He ordered all of the men to be arrested and, if they refused to obey the command, he would place the men in jail and put them under arrest for the rest of the summer. All of the workers were arrested and put on a watchlist to keep them under arrest. On Friday the 28th a riot was reported and, for the next few days, the distillery was closed. The bandits were not found and the Governor ordered them to be released in the morning of Friday, Dec. 20, and it was reported that no trace of the bandits remained. After a few days of surveillance the governor sent the governor's agents to search the building for more evidence of what might be taken out. They found nothing, except for a small amount of cinders, which they concluded had been thrown in. The governor sent a telegram to the Governor, telling him that there had been no report of a raid on the distillery.
There are no recorded reports of a raid on a distillery in New York or in Baltimore. This is not an unusual occurrence since there have been several reports that the distillery at Jefferson had been searched. In one of these reports, an examination of a box of whiskey found a rifle, two revolver bullets, and six barrels of whiskey. A second box of whiskey was examined, and also found that there were three shotgun shells and a gun. An examination of the distillery at Jefferson, Md., showed that there was no evidence of any weapons in the building, although the men were under the impression that the bandits were the same men who terkandungd the loaded trucks. A very similar raid of the distillery at Jefferson, Md., was reported on September 15th, 1904, and the raid was continued untilidus the following September, 1908. The raid took place about three miles from Jefferson. In September, 1908, the Governor and his Department of the Interior sent deputies, and an agent of the United States Army, to search the building. The Governor then requested all deliverymen in the distillery to come out and to give a report to the Governor. They showed to take their deliverances in a different manner than the previous time, since they appeared to have taken the loaded trucks and touring cars and placed them inside the distillery.
For the next twenty days several of the deliverers were arrested. On September 12th a report was issued by the Governor and the Department

prediction.region:
Raiders in Frederick Land Haul of $84,000: Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey is Loaded into Autos

Early today, twenty armed bandits, travelling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery near Frederick, Maryland. They made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey, leaving three government watchmen bound and gagged with a threat of instant death if they raised an alarm. 

Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck, laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey, was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore pike, there is no clue to the direction taken by the caravan, although it is thought that the truck train may have broken down.

Upon notification of the raid, the Washington Police Department threw a cordon around the city and kept a close watch on every road that the stolen liquor might be brought into the District.

The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance day and night by bandit spies who learned every movement of the watchmen.

With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen  John R. Hemp of Burkettaville, MD, William Hart of Baltimore, and John Moredock of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged, and an armed man stood over them until the raiders left more than two hours later. 

From fifty to sixty barrels of aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons in all, were rolled from the building and loaded onto the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4 o'clock in the morning to complete the loading of the caravan. Then, the motorcycle outposts reported that the roads were clear. 

The watchmen were warned against any attempt to escape, and the caravan made off. Hemp finally broke loose. He found the telephone lines had been cut, and he was forced to walk a long distance before he could spread the alarm. Sheriff James C. Jones led the investigation.
