The trucks and touring cars were loaded into the back of the large motor cars and the four-wheel drive cars. They arrived in the distance and, after several hours, broke in. The bandits were tied with ropes and they were all pinned down by the guards. The guards were ordered to put down their guns and run as fast as possible to the nearest gun house. The guards were not allowed to look after the prisoners, and the men were then all tied to a cot. The four-wheel drive cars were driven in and it is thought they were hauled out and driven to the next gun house. The robbers were soon all in the car. They took three horses and four people. The two thieves- one was a local sheriff's horse. One was a police constable of Baltimore and the other was a local sheriff's horse. Sheriff Jones found it hard to resist, but in the ensuing hours he succeeded in bringing the four-wheel drive cars back from the woods, and on the following evening he had enough of them and the two thieves-one of them was a local sheriff's horse. He took them to the nearest gun house, but a day later he had to send them to the nearest gun house. In spite of the presence of two officers, one from the police department and the other from the sheriff's office, and the two of them on horseback, Sheriff Jones was able to beat back the bandits with his own horse and horseback. Two of the two of the thieves-one was a local sheriff's horse and the other a town police horse-took the two horses and left them with the bandits. They were led out to the nearest gun house, which was near the woods, where a guard was stationed. The carriages were driven down to the house where the guards were stationed. The robbers were driven out of the house and out of sight by the guard. The horses were all tied together, but with two or three broken harnesses the horses were driven down to the next gun house. A guard with a horse was stationed in front of the house. The guards watched them for a long time and they began to tire out and the horse was allowed to loose. The carriages were stopped and three of the two thieves who had broken the harness were removed and the men were placed under guard. A guard brought a horse to the house and the thieves rode off in one of the carriages. The carriages were driven through the woods in an east direction and they arrived at the town's gun house. The guards and horses were tied in two places, with one harness tied to a tie rope and the other tied to a rope wire. When they were all tied, the horses were led out of the house and the guard began to ride on the horses. The men were then led back through the woods to the house where the guards were stationed. The guards were watching the horses and when the men were brought in, one of them ran through the house and broke a chain through the horse's tail. The thieves, after several hours, were removed from the house and the horses were driven away. Sheriff Jones and the rest of the members of the Maryland police force who had been in the woods were ordered to be ready to escort the thieves to a gun house when they were finally caught. The two thieves and one of the carriages were led out to the next gun house, where the guards were stationed. When the guards had seen their horse and their horses were driven off, the two thieves got back in and drove off. The other two stole a horse and drove off. The guards were called to the scene and the two thieves were put on board the carriages and transported to the next gun house. A guard was ordered to put down his gun and watch out for the thieves and a guard was called to take charge of the horse. The two thieves stole another horse and

It was done in an amateurish manner and the Government authorities, on learning of it, at once began investigation. The first evidence obtained indicated that a special force was engaged in the work. This was soon confirmed by a raid on a distillery belonging to John C. and E. H. Smith. On the 9th they were both arrested, but later released. A few weeks ago there was a raid on a distillery owned by E. J. Rau. One man was arrested and later released. The raiders appear to have a peculiar system of communication. Their leader may be in jail. Others of the band may be trying to avoid arrest. Another band may be in hiding. They may be waiting to strike again. The Horpey Distillery. In October, during the past winter, a raid was made on another distillery belonging to Horpey. About 30 men were employed in the distillery, and the men were armed with revolvers. All the liquor, which was worth about $40,000 was seized. It was believed that the raiders, who were well armed and had much knowledge of the distillery, had stolen some of the old whiskey recently purchased by the Government for use on the Northern Pacific Railway. prediction.region: were hauled off at once. The caravan was headed for the state line of Maryland and the Maryland road, which leads to Baltimore. The watchmen were held in irons at the headquarters of the Ington police department, and were taken on a tour of Baltimore and neighboring points. No attempt to get news of the raid by telephone was made. The watchmen are being held without bail until their trial. The raid was evidently planned with extreme care. All of the watchmen were known to one and another of the bandits and it was believed that they would not try to escape. As it turned out, no attempt at escape was made, and it seems possible the bandits did the raid from a plan of concealment. The police are seeking for any one who may know the identity of the man who represented himself as an internal revenue agent. The bandits are thought to be about twenty in number, all armed with revolvers and knives and they were all dressed in brown coats and striped pants and carried black caps. They wore handkerchiefs tied tightly over their mouths.</s>

Raiders in Frederick Land Haul of $84,000: Watchman Bound and Gagged While Old Whiskey Is Loaded into Autos"

Travelling with a motor caravan and armed motorcycle scouts, twenty armed bandits swooped down on the Old Horpey Distillery near Frederick, Maryland, early today. They made off with $84,000 worth of choice old whiskey and left three government watchmen bound and gagged under threat of instant death if they tried to raise an alarm. 

Beyond the fact that an abandoned truck laden with seventeen barrels of the stolen whiskey was found eight miles from Frederick on the Baltimore Pike, there is no clue to the direction the caravan took. It is thought the truck train may have broken down. The Washington Police Department, upon receiving notification of the raid, threw a cordon about the city, and a close watch was kept on every road that the stolen liquor might be brought into the district. 

The raid was evidently carried out after days of thorough preparation. The distillery is thought to have been under close surveillance, day and night, by bandit spies who learned every movement of the watchmen.

With motorcycles far to the front and following as a rear guard, the twenty bandits, with three big automobile trucks and four touring cars, drove up to the distillery at 2 o'clock this morning. While the motorcycle men scattered to guard every approach to the building, fifteen of the bandits broke into the office and overpowered the three watchmen: John R. Hemp of Burkettaville, Maryland; William Hart of Baltimore; and John Moredock of Baltimore. The three watchmen were tightly bound and gagged, and an armed man stood over them until the raiders left more than two hours later. Around fifty to sixty barrels of aged whiskey, approximately 2,106 gallons in all, were rolled from the building and loaded onto the trucks and touring cars. It took the bandits until nearly 4 o'clock to complete the loading of the caravan. Then the motorcycle outposts reported the roads clear. The watchmen were admonished against any attempt to escape, and the caravan made off. 

Hemp finally broke loose, and he found the telephone lines had been cut.

The following text was printed in the Daily News on February 1:
FREDERICK, Md.  Sheriff James C. Jones, of the City of Frederick, and members of the Frederick Police Department on Friday morning, observed that the owners of an old liquor building were trying to escape from the city by running down the street, a distance of about two miles, in a manner that could only be described as a "dismal" attempt.
The sheriff also informed the people of the crime, who then hurried in to the offices. The deputies, with the aid of horse-drawn and carriages, and the troopers, were stationed at the door to catch the robbers, who escaped by running along the street and out of sight.
They made some attempts to break in through the front windows of the building, but were met with the same obstacle as had been done in the case of the robbery, which was accomplished by the horse-drawn vehicle in the street.
The sheriff told the police that he found the truck tracks and that the bandit men were behind them, but that there were no other signs of the bandits. The robbers were arrested and the property taken into the custody of the Sheriff's Department.
The following is from the Daily News:
FREDERICK, Md.FREDERICK, Md., February 8, 1884.  The following text was printed in the Daily News on February 8.
FREDERICK, Md., February 8, 1884.  Sheriff Jones, of the City of Frederick, and members of the Frederick Police Department, observed this morning that the owners of an old liquor building were trying to escape from the city by running down the street, a distance of about two miles, in a manner that could only be described as a "dismal" attempt.
The deputies, with the aid of horse-drawn and carriages, and the troopers, were stationed at the door to catch the robbers, who escaped by running along the street and out of sight.
They made some attempts to break in through the front windows of the building, but were met with the same obstacle as had been done in the case of the robbery, which was accomplished by the horse-drawn vehicle in the street.
The robbers were arrested and the property taken into the custody of the Sheriff's Department.</s>

groundtruth.region: Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt -1 Mr Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secre- tary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sun- day films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's De- partment. He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. _ , Yesterday William Fred- erick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, pro- duced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Thcatretc, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, j They aie being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Hairop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian 1 hcatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors' Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Thcatrctle on Sunday. August 12. for. which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche ,Hattam, the Ausira lian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd.. foi screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to giant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatic oi a public house. ' The hearing was fuither adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mi. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead nnd Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

groundtruth.region: Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt -1 Mr Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secre- tary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sun- day films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's De- partment. He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. _ , Yesterday William Fred- erick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, pro- duced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Thcatretc, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, j They aie being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Hairop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian 1 hcatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors' Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Thcatrctle on Sunday. August 12. for. which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche ,Hattam, the Ausira lian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd.. foi screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to giant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatic oi a public house. ' The hearing was fuither adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house. The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt 
Mr. Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secretary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sunday films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department. He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. 

Yesterday, William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. 

Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald, of Spring Street, Sydney. They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-1946. Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. 

NEW SUMMONSES 
The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday, August 12, for which an admission charge was made. Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty Ltd., and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday, August 19. 

Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. 

MINISTER'S RIGHT 
Mr. C. Begg (for Scheinwald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. It is not for the Court to interfere. The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house." 

The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley, K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire, K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

(Mr. John W. Smythe was one of the first lawyers to be called to the Bar by the Supreme Court of Victoria, and was appointed in November, 1913. During the First World War he was a member of the Australian Imperial Force. He was called to the New South Wales Bar in November, 1919, and to the Victorian Bar in January, 1922. He was a Justice of the Supreme Court of Victoria from February, 1934, until his appointment to the Supreme Court of New South Wales in September, 1944. He was appointed to the Court of Appeal in 1944, when the High Court of Australia was formed. He was President of the Court of Appeal from November, 1946, to April, 1947. Mr. Smythe was a Deputy Speaker in the Victorian Parliament from January, 1920, until his appointment to the High Court of Australia. He was appointed to the High Court of Australia in April, 1947.

On 3 October, 1940. Mr. Smythe married, by his parents' authority, the former Mrs. M. F. Smythe of Melbourne. Their marriage was dissolved in May, 1946.

Mr. Smythe died on 14 March, 1957, at Melbourne, and is survived by his wife and three sons.

Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt 
Mr. Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secretary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sunday films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department. He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. 

Yesterday, William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. 

Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald, of Spring Street, Sydney. They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-1946. Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. 

NEW SUMMONSES 
The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday, August 12, for which an admission charge was made. Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty Ltd., and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday, August 19. 

Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. 

MINISTER'S RIGHT 
Mr. C. Begg (for Scheinwald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. It is not for the Court to interfere. The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house." 

The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley, K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire, K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

The following is a short extract of a letter sent to Mr. Bagot, on July 6, 1916, by Mr. Jack Taylor, president of the American Film and Dramatic Club, of which Mr. Bagot is the secretary and chairman. The following is also a brief report of the proceedings of the American Film and Dramatic Club, of which Mr. Bagot is secretary and chairman, held at the Central Court in Sydney on July 2, 1916: 1. Mr. D. A. D. Evatt, the solicitor for Mr. Evatt, was admitted into the Court, and called for his evidence, but declined to give evidence. 2. The prosecuting officer was then admitted, and called for his evidence. 3. Mr. Bagot gave an extract from his statement of the charges made by the solicitor for Mr. Evatt. 4. The plaintiff and defendant, Mr. Evatt and Mr. Jack Taylor, respectively, agreed that they were not in a position to give a full statement, and, for that reason, agreed to adhere to the rule previously agreed upon, according to which, in future, the evidence would be to be taken from the plaintiff, and the evidence from the defendant. 5. The plaintiff and the defendant then took their seats. 6. It was observed that no formality would have been required by either of them to give their statements in this court. 7. Mr. Bagot observed that the plaintiff had stated, in the statement given in the statement of the charges made by the solicitor for Mr. Evatt, that the films were given in the form of Sunday evening programmes. Mr. Bagot stated that the fact that there were films of the type to which he referred was not proved. 8. Mr. Bagot was then ordered to call a jury. 9. Mr. J. C. H. M. T. Bradley, Mr. W. H. J. Smythe, and Mr. C. A. S. F. M. W. H. Maguire, who were in the jury box, and who were present at the moment, were ordered to return a verdict of not guilty. Mr. Bradley was the first of the jury to take his seat, and to enter his verdict. He returned: "We do not find that any person guilty of an offence." Mr. Bradley then proceeded to enter a second verdict, to the effect that no person had been convicted. Mr. Maguire was the second of the jury to take his seat, and to enter his verdict. He returned: "The evidence is clear. The film is a play, and there is nothing more in the case." The court adjourned until November 2, when a further sitting will be held. Mr. T. C. Bagot, acting secretary of the American Film and Dramatic Club, of which Mr.

Begg, Alexander Hamilton (Hamish), first Baron Haversham (18891970)
https://adbonline.anu.edu.au/biogs/A170145b.htm
Hamish Begg, the younger son of Alexander Begg and Louisa (ne MacKenzie), was born on 24 May 1889 at Brompton, Melbourne, and educated at Scotch College. In 1905, at the age of 16, he was apprenticed to the law firm of Russell & Co. He was admitted as a solicitor on 23 September 1909 and was called to the bar on 10 December 1911. In March 1913 he was appointed Crown prosecutor for South Australia and moved to Adelaide, later becoming Queen's Council on 12 December 1923. On 18 January 1927 he resigned from the Crown prosecutorship to concentrate on his legal practice. In 1930 he was elected a member of the Legislative Council of South Australia, representing the electoral district of East Torrens, and served until 1944. On 18 December 1930 he was appointed to the South Australian cabinet as attorney-general and minister for justice. He remained in these portfolios until the formation of the Labor government in 1933, when he returned to the Legislative Council.
A member of the Liberal Party, he entered federal parliament at the 1934 election as member for East Sydney, defeating the incumbent Joseph Cook by a slender margin of five votes. With the assistance of the United Australia Party he was appointed treasurer in Stanley Bruce's ministry on 19 April 1934, becoming minister for defence on 20 November of that year, following the death of Alexander Hore-Ruthven. In 1937 he became minister for the Army and for defence forces. When the Bruce ministry was reconstructed in October 1937 he resumed his portfolio of defence forces, which he retained until the election of the Labor Party in 1941.

Mr. Begg said: "The Court has to be satisfied that it would be a serious problem for Mr. Humphrey to stand in court and hear this Court's decision of last Tuesday. "I think we are looking forward to the court's ruling. "The Crown would be very happy to hear the Court make such a decision, which we hope will lead to good and speedy justice and the good of the public. "If the Court cannot, on that basis, accept such a ruling from the Crown, it is very much up to the Crown to decide if it is appropriate." Mr. Begg said: "I want to get a clear record of what is being done in the courtroom today. "In a courtroom, in which the Court has not sat for months or weeks or months or even months, and the Court has not been in a place where there is a full-time role or on days or even days, I think it is fair to say that it is very difficult to hear a decision in the courtroom." Mr. Begg added: "There is a feeling, I guess, that is going to prevail in court that the Court should find that it was necessary to intervene, and that it was, in fact, necessary to intervene." Mr. Begg was in Sydney for this trial on October 26 and Mr. Begg said he would be in court later that day. The case has been referred to the Australian Federal Court for proceedings at a later date. Mr. Begg was on leave before being heard. A hearing for Mr. Begg and Mr. Cunningham was on November 9. Mr. Begg, in his brief for the Government on Saturday, said the Minister's position on Sunday evening was "wrong". Mr. Cunningham said: "The Minister did not make a decision. "He chose to make that decision because, to me, that is a very bad thing for the public good. That is not the public's choice. "And so if this Minister decides to put a stop to it then that is a very bad thing for society. "He can sit in court on the weekend and make it a very big problem, but Deacon is going to see to it he puts this case back and there will be no need for the decision of the Court today and the Court will have had to deal with it on its own." Mr. Beavers, S.M., refused to allow the Chief Secretary, Mr. Clive Evatt, to be represented at the Central Court during the Sunday films case hearing. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department. He stated that the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister.

Yesterday, William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents that had been subpoenaed earlier but were not produced at the hearing. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook of the King's Cross Theatrette and Natan Scheinwald of Spring Street, Sydney, who were being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-1946. Mr. Harrop was also the honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association.

Further summonses were laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty Ltd., and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday, August 19th. 

Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot stated yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings, and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behavior. 

Mr. C. Begg (for Scheinwald) stated that Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said, "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. It is not for the Court".

METROPOLITAN DISTRICT COURT. FRIDAY. (Before his Honor Judge GRIGSON.) 

BROOMHEAD v. PARRY. 

This was a claim by John William Broomhead, of Elizabeth Street, Balmain, against Griffith Parry, of Crescent Street, Balmain, for 17 5s, amount of a dishonored promissory note. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

MARSHALL & CO., v. WHATMORE. 

John A. Marshall, trading as Marshall and Co, butchers, of Alfred Street, sued W. W. Whatmore, of Bellevue Street, for goods sold and delivered. 
A verdict was given for 11 16s 3d, the amount claimed. 

IZZARD & CO. v. MOIR. 

This was a claim by Robert Irwin, John O'Neil, and George Goldsmith, of Wyong, against A. Moir, of Bowra Wharf, Sydney, for 10 11s 1d, goods sold and delivered. 
Verdict for the plaintiffs for the amount claimed. 

KAVANAGH v. NICE. 

J. Kavanagh, of 114 Castlereagh Street, sued Mrs Joseph Nice, of 70 King Street, for 16 4s, for goods sold and delivered. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

SIMMS & CO. v. ROBEY. 

Henry B. Simms trading as Henry Simms and Co, importers, of York Street, Sydney, sued Henry Robey, of Cleveland Street, Surry Hills, for 25 10s, amount due on a dishonored promissory note. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

FIELD v. WRIGHT. 

Henry Field, son manufacturer, of Oxford Street, Paddington, claimed 17 13s 7d from David Wright, dealer, of Urana Street, Cossack, for goods sold and delivered. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

SAYWELL v. ALLEN. 

Thomas Saywell, carrying on business as the South Clifton Coal-mining Company, sued Thomas Allen, of Druitt Street, Sydney, timber merchant, for 13 18s, goods sold and delivered. 
A verdict was given for the amount claimed. 

GREEN v. CHAUNCEY. 

Emanuel Green, of 2 Globe Street, Paddington, sued H. R. Chauncey, of 108 Pitt Street, Sydney, for 2 6s, money paid by plaintiff to the defendant for payment by him to the Crown for the purchase of conditional purchase 88-28 at Windsor. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

The Court then adjourned.

A large number of men, women, and children were brought up in custody during the morning. Mr. R. G. H. Campbell presided. 253. AH'rT'i.K. J. THOMPSON, of George-street, charged with assaulting Mr. Thomas Crawford, was fined 1 and costs. CRAWFORD, of George-street, charged with having a breech-loading rifle in unlawful possession, was discharged. WILLIAM THOMAS, for an assault in William-street, on Tuesday last, was committed for trial, bail being fixed at 100. - THE HARBOUR BOARD. (Before the Right Hon. the Governor, in person.) THURSDAY. The business done included the following matters:- 1. Resolved, That this Board sanction the application of the City Council for 700 towards the expense of the Harbour Improvement Fund. 2. Resolved, That in future all shipping engaged in the Port of Sydney to the amount of 250 tons or over be compelled to register their boats and lighters. 3. Resolved, That the surveyor be instructed to ascertain, without delay, if any lands within the limits of the Harbour Board are suitable for the purpose of providing sites for the new markets to be erected by the Council. 4. Resolved, That tenders for the erection of the new markets be invited by the Surveyor from builders, and that the lowest tenderer be accepted, with the provision that he will erect the buildings within three months. 5. Resolved, That the Surveyor be requested to report to the next meeting whether any lands have been obtained for the purpose of erecting a new market. 6. Resolved, That the tender of Mr. J. B. Pemfry for 1000 for building two lighters be accepted. 7. Resolved, That the Harbour Board be informed that it was not the intention of the Government to take any steps towards the erection of a lighthouse on South Head until the Board had completed the investigation into the question of lighting. 8. Resolved, That the Chairman, on behalf of the Board, sign the agreement entered into by the Chairman and Surveyor with Messrs. Hale and Sons, to pay 300 for a site for the new market, and on the expiration of six months of such site to pay another 100, and on the expiration of twelve months to pay the balance of 100. The Board then adjourned until Monday next. - THE EXPORT MARKET. (From our own Correspondent.) TUES

CONCERTS IN THE PRESENT JURISDICTION
The Court decided the cases against Mr. P S Darnell, of Hartnell, and Mr. H. H. Johnson, of Hartnell, for breach of contract in respect of the sale of coal for the purchase of condit oil, and a verdict was given for Mr. Johnson. The Court concluded by the payment of an interest on the sum paid for the sale of coal for the purchase of condit oil. The Company was not bound to pay the sum to Mr. Johnson; he was therefore compensated. The Company was then liable for 25,000, to the plaintiff for the loss incurred.</s>

prediction.region:
METROPOLITAN DISTRICT COURT. FRIDAY. (Before his Honor Judge GRIGSON.) 

BROOMHEAD v. PARRY. 

This was a claim by John William Broomhead, of Elizabeth Street, Balmain, against Griffith Parry, of Crescent Street, Balmain, for 17 5s, amount of a dishonored promissory note. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

MARSHALL & CO., v. WHATMORE. 

John A. Marshall, trading as Marshall and Co, butchers, of Alfred Street, sued W. W. Whatmore, of Bellevue Street, for goods sold and delivered. 
A verdict was given for 11 16s 3d, the amount claimed. 

IZZARD & CO. v. MOIR. 

This was a claim by Robert Irwin, John O'Neil, and George Goldsmith, of Wyong, against A. Moir, of Bowra Wharf, Sydney, for 10 11s 1d, goods sold and delivered. 
Verdict for the plaintiffs for the amount claimed. 

KAVANAGH v. NICE. 

J. Kavanagh, of 114 Castlereagh Street, sued Mrs Joseph Nice, of 70 King Street, for 16 4s, for goods sold and delivered. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

SIMMS & CO. v. ROBEY. 

Henry B. Simms trading as Henry Simms and Co, importers, of York Street, Sydney, sued Henry Robey, of Cleveland Street, Surry Hills, for 25 10s, amount due on a dishonored promissory note. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

FIELD v. WRIGHT. 

Henry Field, son manufacturer, of Oxford Street, Paddington, claimed 17 13s 7d from David Wright, dealer, of Urana Street, Cossack, for goods sold and delivered. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

SAYWELL v. ALLEN. 

Thomas Saywell, carrying on business as the South Clifton Coal-mining Company, sued Thomas Allen, of Druitt Street, Sydney, timber merchant, for 13 18s, goods sold and delivered. 
A verdict was given for the amount claimed. 

GREEN v. CHAUNCEY. 

Emanuel Green, of 2 Globe Street, Paddington, sued H. R. Chauncey, of 108 Pitt Street, Sydney, for 2 6s, money paid by plaintiff to the defendant for payment by him to the Crown for the purchase of conditional purchase 88-28 at Windsor. 
A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. 

The Court then adjourned.

ROYAL COURT. Sydney, 25th January, 1895. Before His Excellency the Governor, Sir Hercules Robinson.
SATURDAY, JANUARY 27, 1894. Before His Excellency the Governor, Sir Hercules Robinson, the Chief Justice, and Mr. Justice Higinbotham. MORRISON V. BUCHAN. William Morrison, merchant, of Glebe, sued John Buchan, of Pyrmont, dealer, for 48 3s, for goods sold and delivered. A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed. -NOTE.An appeal was entered by the defendant, which is yet undetermined. JUDGE V. BENNETT. W. P. Bennett, solicitor, of Redfern, sued James H. Judge, of Sydney, iron merchant, for 5 11s. 6d. for fees claimed by the plaintiff for attending to a matter which was settled by arbitration. Mr. Justice Higinbotham, in his ruling, said that if the plaintiff's case planning, the defendant's witness should be examined, and that if the defendant had been prepared to pay the fees claimed he would have taken the opinion of the plaint cell's attorney, and would have done so at once. The jury returned a verdict feas the plaintiff for the amount claimed, with interest. JOHNSON V. BURTON. W. T. Johnson, butcher, of George-street, Sydney, sued Henry Burton, of 396 Crown-street, Sydney, for 6 17s. for goods sold and delivered, which was a dishonoured promissory note. The jury returned a verdict for the amount claimed, with interest, and the Judge in his ruling said that the plaintiff was entitled to a decree for the amount claimed, which, with interest, amounted to 7 19s 4d. It was further stated that if the defendant had failed to pay at the time the note fell due it would have been lawful for the plaintiff to have taken the property on which the note was endorsed, and also to have sought to obtain payment of the amount due on the promissory note, and that if he had made such demand, he would be entitled to retain the goods and to seek for his debt in the court. The court, in this case, were of opinion that the plaintiff was entitled to a decree for the amount claimed, with interest. In this case an appeal was entered by the defendant, which is yet undetermined. BUSH V. LLOYD. Henry Bush, of 171 Pitt-street, Sydney, dealer, sued Thomas Lloyd, of Newtown, blacksmith, for 3 15s. 6d, for goods sold and delivered. A verdict was given for the amount claimed. DYER V. RUTTENBURY.

(Before the Honourable Mr Justice MacPherson, for the District of New South Wales, and the Honourable Mr Justice King, for the District of Queensland). -ROBERTS V. LONDON, RICHARDSON V. MANSERV, and MARTIN V. ALLEN were tried on Tuesday, before Mr Justice MacPherson, in the Court of Criminal Sessions at Parramatta, and were found guilty of the murder of Wm. C. Roberts, of Paddington. The sentence was death. The Court also found Robert Richardson, Henry Robinson, and Charles Martin, guilty of the murder of Thomas Mason, of George-street, Parramatta, and of assisting the said murder, and the sentence was death. The trial of the three prisoners had been continued until to-day. A few minutes after nine the prisoners were brought into the Court, and it was the first time since their imprisonment that they had been seen in public. They wore cuffs round their arms, and black coats over their shoulders. When they had been taken up to the bar the Court was thrown into a profound silence, and the three prisoners, the same as in their last trial, were taken into custody. -At 9.30 the Court was again crowded, and the attention of the crowded Court, and of the vast assemblage of spectators, was attracted by the entrance of George Mitchell, and by the examination which he made of John Latham, who is one of the prosecution witnesses. George Mitchell and Latham left the Court together, the Court being again thrown into a profound silence, and the prisoners were again taken up to the bar. During the examination Latham gave the names of four persons who had seen Mitchell after the robbery of the stage. Mitchell said, he had met George Mitchell twice; once he had spoken to him for five or six minutes, and the second time for seven minutes. After he had been examined Latham was taken up into custody and taken to the Police-station. The prisoner Mitchell and the three others were then taken up, and in the absence of the Court were again taken into custody and taken to the police-station. At 9.45 Mr Justice King returned, and the three prisoners were again taken up into custody, and the trial was adjourned until to-morrow morning at 10. 30. Mr J. S. Treloar was in attendance in the Court as solicitor for the prosecution. The Attorney General, Mr H. B. Willis, also appeared.

METROPOLITAN DISTRICT COURT. FRIDAY. (Before His Honour Judge Gradson.)

RISHTON V. PARRY. This was a claim by John William Broomhead, of Elizabeth Street, Balmain, against Griffith Parry, of Crescent Street, Balmain, for 17 5s, the amount of a dishonoured promissory note. A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed.

MARSHALL & CO. V. WHITMORE. John A. Marshall, trading as Marshall and Co, butchers, of Alfred Street, sued W. W. Whitmore, of Bellevue Street, for goods sold and delivered. A verdict was given for 11 16s 3d, the amount claimed.

IZZARD & CO. V. MOIR. This was a claim by Robert Irwin, John O'Neil, and George Goldsmith, of Wyong, against A. Moir, of Bowra Wharf, Sydney, for 10 11s 1d, goods sold and delivered. Verdict for the plaintiffs for the amount claimed.

KAVANAGH V. NICE. J. Kavanagh, of 114 Castlereagh Street, sued Mrs Joseph Nice, of 70 King Street, for 16 4s, goods sold and delivered. A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed.

SIMMS & CO. V. ROBEY. Henry B. Simms, trading as Henry Simms and Co, importer, of York Street, Sydney, sued Henry Robey, of Cleveland Street, Surry Hills, for 25 10s, the amount due on a dishonoured promissory note. A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed.

FIELD V. WRIGHT. Henry Field, son manufacturer, of Oxford Street, Paddington, claimed 117 13s 7d from David Wright, dealer, of Victoria Street, Cosford, for goods sold and delivered. A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed.

SAYWELL V. ALLEN. Thomas Saywell, carrying on business as the South Clifton Coal-mining Company, sued Thomas Allen, of Druitt Street, Sydney, timber merchant, for 13 18s, goods sold and delivered. A verdict was given for the plaintiff for the amount claimed.

BULLETIN OF THE SOUTH EAST CORPORATION OF SYDNEY
PAPERS FOR THE WEEK ENDING WEDNESDAY, MARCH 21, 1876.
LATE NOTICE. The South Eastern Railway and Harbour Board having on the 9th of January, 1876, made an application for leave to lay a road on the north side of the Nepean river, at Windsor, in order to enable the construction of the bridge of which it is the object to make a part, a notice of motion having been made, notice is hereby given that a meeting of the inhabitants of the above-named wards of the city, to be held on Tuesday, the 17th instant, at the Crown Hotel, will consider and give its decision in reference to that application.
On Saturday, the 21st instant, the meeting will take place at 8 o'clock in the forenoon.
Mr. John Murray, Chairman,
Mr. D W. Ewing, Secretary,
Mr. George Smith, Chairman of the Board,
Mr. George McLean, Engineer,
Mr. Charles W. Brown, Surveyor-General.
Notice is hereby given that the meeting to be held at the corner of Pitt-street and George-street, on Monday, the 16th inst., will consider the question of the incorporation of an agricultural society.
On Thursday, the 21st instant, a meeting of the South East Railway and Harbour Board will take place.
The minutes of the meeting of last week were signed by Mr. John Murray, Chairman, Messrs. D W. Ewing, Charles W. Brown, and G. Smith, Secretary.
A few days ago the following notice appeared in the Press.
